# React Performance (afenda-xforge)

**Server Components first** — see `frontend-app.mdc`. This rule applies to **`'use client'`** leaves and interactive UI only.

Profile before micro-optimizing. MCP: `/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/reactCompiler`, `/docs/app/getting-started/linking-and-navigating`.

## Default stack (this repo)

- **RSC** for data fetch and static structure — smallest `'use client'` boundary
- **React Compiler** is not enabled globally — do not sprinkle `useMemo` / `useCallback` / `memo` without a measured need
- If enabling compiler later: `reactCompiler: true` in `next.config` (MCP docs) reduces manual memo

## Client component rules

| Do | When |
|----|------|
| Derive during render | Cheap values from props/state |
| `useMemo` / `useCallback` | Large list transforms, stable deps for memoized children, proven hot paths |
| Split state/context | Separate fast-changing from slow-changing values |
| Stable `key` | Entity id — not array index on dynamic lists |
| `dynamic(() => import(...))` | Heavy client-only modules |

| Avoid | Why |
|-------|-----|
| `memo` on every export | Overhead; compiler not on |
| `useEffect` for derived state | Compute in render |
| New objects/functions in render passed to memoized children | Defeats memo — hoist or memoize |

## Next.js navigation & loading

- **`next/link`** for internal routes — prefetch is automatic; use `prefetch={false}` only on huge link lists
- Dynamic routes → add **`loading.tsx`** so partial prefetch + instant feedback (MCP linking-and-navigating)
- Slow transitions → `useLinkStatus` pending UI (client leaf)
- Route data → Server Component + `<Suspense>` — not client fetch on mount

## Assets

- **`next/image`** with `width`/`height` or `fill` — not raw `<img>` for app UI
- Remote images → `images.remotePatterns` in `next.config`

## Anti-patterns

```tsx
// ❌ Client fetch + spinners where RSC + Suspense fits
'use client'
useEffect(() => { fetch('/api/items').then(setItems) }, [])

// ❌ Index keys on reorderable lists
items.map((item, i) => <Row key={i} ... />)

// ✅ Server fetch; client only for interaction
// page.tsx (Server) → <ItemList items={items} />
```

## When optimizing for real

1. React DevTools Profiler or Next.js dev indicators on the slow interaction
2. Confirm bottleneck is client re-render — not missing `loading.tsx`, over-prefetch, or an oversized client bundle
3. Prefer moving work server-side before adding memo layers

```bash
pnpm --filter app typecheck
pnpm check
```
